   133	| G4 | lease live | `now − last_R` (s) | `< t_lease` **[UNVERIFIED]** | continuous | ⇒ expiry | this doc (**proposed**); baseline motivates continuous output via `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` |
   134	
   135	Hysteresis/dwell for the caution band (`dwell_clear`) and the re-arm dwell (`dwell_rearm`) are
   136	defined in §2.2/§3.2; both are **[UNVERIFIED]**. Items traced
   137	to "proposed" require a baseline/contracts change and cannot be treated as baseline-authorised
   138	until made so.
   139	
   140	### 1.3 Why the authority gate cannot live in ArduPilot
   141	
   142	- **ArduPilot's covariance is censored.** It clamps reported horizontal accuracy at **100 m**;
   143	  its EKF variance cannot distinguish a 5 m solution from a 5 km divergence — the exact
   144	  discrimination G2 requires. The unclamped protection limit exists only upstream.
   145	- **ArduPilot cannot see the LEO integrity state** (calibration-ID match, ephemeris age,
   146	  per-pass transmit-bias health, cross-sensor residuals) that G2/G3 test.
   147	- **ArduPilot cannot see companion liveness** (G4): a stalled companion looks, from
   148	  ArduPilot's side, like a GPS gone quiet.
   149	- **`gnss_authority` / profile selection are companion concepts.**
   150	
   151	ArduPilot is therefore a downstream actuator that is **never relied on to judge navigation
   152	integrity**. Its own GPS/EKF failsafe actions are configured so that loss/degradation of
   153	`GPS_INPUT` **cannot itself command an autonomous manoeuvre** (RTL/Loiter/disarm) — because
   154	that manoeuvre is the hazard (§2). Exact failsafe parameter values are **[UNVERIFIED]** and are
   155	a SITL-validated deliverable pinned to a firmware commit + artifact checksum.
   156	
   157	---
   158	
   159	## 2. What revokes steering authority
   160	
   161	### 2.1 Revocation semantics, and the actual signal path to ArduPilot (fixes findings 2, 3, 11, 14)
   162	
   163	Revocation is never a manoeuvre:
   164	
   165	> **Revocation = stop steering + alarm + hand to helm.**
   166	
   167	Software shall **never** autonomously select RTL, Loiter or disarm (failure mode 9; baseline
   168	final degradation row). But "stop steering + hand to helm" is only a real safety action if
   169	the mechanism that delivers it to ArduPilot is defined. It is **not** delivered by `GPS_INPUT`
   170	— that message is navigation data, not a control-authority interface. Two physically distinct
   171	cases exist, and the previous draft wrongly treated them as one:
   172	
   173	**Case A — companion alive, link up** (integrity/limit breach, lease expiry while the process
   174	still runs, or a helm-commanded disarm). The companion performs an *active* revocation:
   175	
   176	1. It commands ArduPilot into a helm/manual control mode over MAVLink (candidate
   177	   `MAV_CMD_DO_SET_MODE` / `SET_MODE` to `MANUAL` or an equivalent helm-controlled mode; exact
   178	   command, mode enum and RC-arbitration parameters **[UNVERIFIED]**, SITL/HIL deliverable).
   179	2. It then ceases / invalidates the `GPS_INPUT` nav injection, consistent with that mode.
   180	3. It raises the alarm (§3.2).
   181	
   182	The ordering to be **verified in SITL/HIL**: the mode transition to manual precedes or is
   183	simultaneous with cessation of nav injection, so that no GPS-timeout failsafe is provoked and
   184	**no commanded turn, throttle change, loiter, RTL, disarm, or actuator discontinuity occurs**;
   185	physical helm input dominates immediately. Until that test passes on pinned firmware, the
   186	"hand to helm" action is **unproven** and is registered as such (§5).
   187	
   188	**Case B — companion process dead, or MAVLink link lost** (whole-process stall, thread death,
   189	cable/connector fault). The companion can send nothing; **its internal watchdog/lease cannot
   190	reach ArduPilot.** ArduPilot observes only the *absence* of `GPS_INPUT` and reacts on its own
   191	`GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` (4000 ms), taking the pre-configured non-manoeuvre action. In this case the
   192	actual responders are **(a) ArduPilot's pre-configured non-manoeuvre GPS-failsafe and (b) the
   193	physical helm / kill-cord — not the internal watchdog.** There is an unavoidable window of up
   194	to `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` during which ArduPilot coasts on the last `GPS_INPUT`; the safety argument
   195	is only that this coast is *bounded*, that the action at its end is *configured non-manoeuvring*,
   196	and that the physical helm dominates throughout. A one-way companion→ArduPilot TX failure is
   197	**not observable to the companion** without a return heartbeat; the companion judges link
   198	health via the ArduPilot→companion MAVLink heartbeat with its own deadline, but even on
   199	detection it cannot correct ArduPilot over the failed channel — detection serves alarm and
   200	logging, not actuator control.
   201	
   202	**Consequently the corrected guarantee is:** *for faults in which the companion keeps
   203	executing, the live supervisor revokes within `t_lease` (Case A).* For companion death or link
   204	loss (Case B) the guarantee degrades to ArduPilot's bounded (~4 s) non-manoeuvre timeout plus
   205	the physical layer. The claim "the companion always revokes before ArduPilot's failsafe" is
   206	withdrawn; `t_lease < GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` matters only in Case A, where it bounds how long a
   207	degraded-but-alive companion may keep asserting before self-revoking.
   208	
   209	### 2.2 Authority state machine and full transition table (fixes findings 4, 5)
   210	
   211	Intended disarm and startup-unarmed are **not** faults and must not alarm. A distinct
   212	**DISARMED** state is introduced; the S2/S3 alarm ladder is reserved for loss of a
   213	*previously granted* lease due to a hazardous condition.
   214	
   215	States: **DISARMED** · **NOMINAL (S0)** · **CAUTION (S1)** · **WARNING (S2)** · **ESCALATED
   216	(S3)** · **LATCHED-SAFE (S4)**.
   217	
   218	| Transition (event) | From | To | Authority | Annunciation |
   219	|---|---|---|---|---|
   220	| process start (G1 false) | — | DISARMED | none | quiet status |
   221	| helm arms, `G2∧G3` on fresh frame (`R`) | DISARMED | NOMINAL | granted | quiet "armed" |
   222	| helm arms, `G2∧G3` not yet met | DISARMED | DISARMED | none | "cannot arm: solution not ready" |
   223	| protection metric ≥ `caution_enter` | NOMINAL | CAUTION | granted | soft pre-alert |
   224	| metric ≤ `caution_clear` for `dwell_clear` | CAUTION | NOMINAL | granted | clear |
   225	| **helm disarms** (G1 commanded false) | NOMINAL/CAUTION | DISARMED | revoked (intended) | quiet handoff confirm — **no alarm** |
   226	| **G2 or G3 false** (fault) | NOMINAL/CAUTION | WARNING | **revoked, latched** | loud alarm, demand ack |
   227	| **G4 lease expiry while alive** | NOMINAL/CAUTION | WARNING | **revoked, latched** | loud alarm, demand ack |
   228	| ack within `T_ack` | WARNING | LATCHED-SAFE | revoked | steady fault |
   229	| no ack for `T_ack` | WARNING | ESCALATED | revoked | max continuous alarm |
   230	| ack | ESCALATED | LATCHED-SAFE | revoked | steady fault |
   231	| re-arm (G1 edge, `G2∧G3`, after `dwell_rearm`) | LATCHED-SAFE / DISARMED | NOMINAL | granted | quiet "armed" |
   232	
   233	Every condition change true→false and false→true has exactly one authority + annunciation
   234	outcome above. Note the distinction the previous draft missed: **G1 falling by helm command is
   235	an intended, quiet disarm**, while **G2/G3 false or G4 expiry are fault revocations that
   236	alarm**. "Any false term drops authority" still holds; only the *annunciation* differs by
   237	cause. Whole-process death (Case B) cannot self-annunciate — it presents to the helm via the
   238	absence of the healthy indication plus any independent annunciator, and to ArduPilot via
   239	GPS timeout.
   240	
   241	### 2.3 Degradation-row mapping (baseline degradation contract)
   242	
   243	"Continue" = estimator keeps running (baseline: authority expiry never stops the estimator);
   244	authority persists only while G1–G4 hold.
   245	
   246	| Baseline degradation row | Supervisor response | Trigger |
   247	|---|---|---|
   248	| GNSS absent or forbidden | Normal denied operation; **denied** profile active; GNSS cannot re-enter fusion (bus ingress). | none (mode) |
   249	| One LEO constellation / RF front end lost | Continue if protection limits met; degrade honestly. | G2 if breached |
   250	| **All LEO observations lost** | DR frames keep renewing G4; authority ends on G2 — protection-limit breach **or** `t_dr` elapsed, whichever first. | G2 (`t_dr` or PL) |
   251	| One magnetometer lost/rejected | Continue on the other calibrated magnetometer, IMU turn dynamics and any selected non-magnetic heading sensor; inflate heading uncertainty. | G2 (heading) if breached |
   252	| **Both magnetometers lost/rejected** | Continue short-term attitude propagation and any selected non-magnetic heading measurement; not passage-capable by inertial integration alone; revoke when heading PL exceeded. | G2 (heading) |
   253	| Speed log lost | Continue; current separation unavailable. | G2 if breached |
   254	| **IMU stream stale** | Propagation untrustworthy → revoke; estimator stays running, fabricates no propagation samples, and journalling and recovery may continue. | G2 (per-source freshness) |
   255	| Frequency reference degrades / sustained heel | Reject biased Doppler per integrity; revoke when limits exceeded. | G2 |
   256	| Sea-surface multipath biases a tracker | Reject/inflate on correlation quality + residuals; persistent correlated residuals revoke. | G2 |
   257	| Ephemeris missing or too old | Do not form/accept affected Doppler (never bypass age gate); revoke only if the surviving solution breaches limits. | **G2 (ephemeris-age gate)** |
   258	| **Companion process stalls** | Live supervisor cannot act (it is the stalled process); responders are ArduPilot's non-manoeuvre timeout + physical layer (Case B, §2.1). Software never selects RTL/Loiter/disarm. | Case B |
   259	| Calibration ID missing/mismatched *(additional row — not one of the 11 literal baseline rows; sourced from the extrinsics rule, `DESIGN_BASELINE.md` §Estimator and degradation contract, "missing or mismatched calibration is an integrity fault that forbids steering authority")* | Authority-blocking integrity fault. | G3 |
   260	
   261	**Orbcomm fusion caveat (fixes B4; per D10).** Orbcomm arrives on an independent, non-coherent
   262	receiver introducing a **second, unmodelled receiver clock**. Per decision **D10**, Orbcomm
   263	observations shall **not enter fusion** until a second receiver-clock state or per-receiver
   264	nuisance term exists; until then they cannot corrupt the steering solution or its protection
   265	limits. This is a safety-relevant integrity constraint on which observations G2 may rest.
   266	
   267	The DR timeout `t_dr` **governs authority only** (baseline; failure mode 3) — it never stops
   268	propagation, observation processing, journalling, or the 10–20 min convergence.
   269	
   270	---
   271	
   272	## 3. The backstop when the human does not respond
   273	
   274	### 3.0 Fault domains and independence (fixes finding 12; coordinator point ii)
   275	
   276	Independence claims are only valid across fault-domain boundaries. The domains are:
   277	
   278	- **Companion process / board (one domain).** Clock service, estimator, integrity monitor
   279	  (module 10), authority supervisor + watchdog (module 11) and MAVLink publisher (module 12)
   280	  all execute here. A **process-level fault** (memory corruption, scheduler stall, a fault
   281	  that simultaneously produces a plausible-wrong solution *and* a passing integrity verdict)
   282	  takes them down **together**. Within this domain, separate modules with design-diverse code
   283	  contain **design faults** of one another (e.g. a finite-difference-checked integrity monitor
   284	  catches a wrong-Jacobian estimator bug), but they contain **no** process-level fault.
   285	- **ArduPilot (separate compute).** Independent of companion process faults, but blind to
   286	  navigation-integrity correctness (censored 100 m view) — it can react to *absence* of input,
   287	  not to plausible-wrong input.
   288	- **Physical helm override + kill-cord (no compute).** Independent of all software; but they
   289	  act on gross vessel behaviour and human presence, not on nav correctness (§3.3).
   290	- **The human.** The only element that can judge that steering "looks wrong". Single point.
   291	
   292	The consequence, stated plainly: **no in-companion module is an independent mitigation of a
   293	companion process-level fault.** Where the earlier draft cited "the same integrity monitor +
   294	watchdog" as mitigation for a companion producing plausible-wrong output (H6), that is
   295	withdrawn. That residual is **uncontrolled by present design** and requires an **out-of-
   296	companion-process independent monitor** which does not yet exist; registered in §5.
   297	
   298	### 3.1 Layer 1 — supervisor monotonic watchdog (bounded scope)
   299	
   300	The lease (§1.1) on the clock service's monotonic domain is renewed only by a fresh,
   301	integrity-passing frame. Its **genuine, defensible job**: while the companion process is still
   302	executing, stop it from continuing to assert steering on a **frozen or stale solution** (H4) —
   303	a frozen estimator does not advance the solution sequence, so `R` does not fire, the lease
   304	expires, and the *live* supervisor executes a Case-A revocation.
   305	
   306	Its **limits**, now stated (correcting the previous over-claim): the watchdog **cannot** act
   307	once its own process has died or the link is lost (Case B) — it is inside the failed domain.
   308	"Authority cannot outlive the solution" therefore holds *for the companion-alive fault class
   309	only*; for companion death/link loss the bound is ArduPilot's ~4 s non-manoeuvre timeout plus
   310	the physical layer, not the internal watchdog. Independence properties that do hold: the
   311	watchdog runs on the monotonic clock (a device/UTC reset or spoofed label cannot extend it),
   312	and its expiry cannot stop the estimator (baseline).
   313	
   314	`t_lease` shall be `< GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` (4000 ms) so that in Case A the companion self-revokes
   315	before its output would age out at ArduPilot. Provisional few×200 ms — **[UNVERIFIED]**.
   316	
   317	### 3.2 Layer 2 — un-acknowledged-alarm escalation ladder, with real hysteresis (fixes finding 13)
   318	
   319	The ladder exists to *summon the helm*, not to replace the helm; because software never
   320	manoeuvres, **the terminal state is not kinetic**. States and transitions are in §2.2. The
   321	caution band uses **distinct entry and clear thresholds with a dwell** (single-threshold logic
   322	from the prior draft was not hysteresis):
   323	
   324	- ordering, for an uncertainty metric (larger = worse): `caution_clear < caution_enter < revoke_threshold`;
   325	- **CAUTION entry:** metric `≥ caution_enter` (this concrete crossing replaces the prior vague
   326	  "margin shrinking" — fixes C3);
   327	- **WARNING:** metric `≥ revoke_threshold`;
   328	- **CAUTION→NOMINAL clear:** metric `≤ caution_clear` sustained for `dwell_clear`;
   329	- all of `caution_enter`, `caution_clear`, `dwell_clear`, `revoke_threshold`, `T_ack`,
   330	  `dwell_rearm` are **[UNVERIFIED]**, frozen before trials against the manoeuvre budget.
   331	
   332	Latched revocation requiring explicit re-arm (§2.2) prevents steering-authority flapping;
   333	the entry/clear band with dwell prevents S0/S1 *alarm* flapping. **Terminal state = ESCALATED
   334	+ max alarm**, indefinitely, with no kinetic action; if the helm never responds the vessel
   335	holds its last physical control state (least-surprising) until the helm or the physical layer
   336	(§3.3) intervenes.
   337	
   338	### 3.3 Layer 3 — physical, controller-independent override (final layer)
   339	
   340	Independent of companion, ArduPilot and MAVLink:
   341	
   342	- **Helm manual override** — steering/throttle mechanically dominates the autopilot at any
   343	  time (baseline precondition). This is how "hand to helm" becomes real motion control, and is
   344	  the only control effective in Case B when software cannot signal.
   345	- **Helm kill-cord** — a physical lanyard that cuts propulsion (failure mode 9). It acts only
   346	  when *pulled* — i.e. when the helmsman is **displaced** (overboard / falls from station).
   347	
   348	**Human-response failure, by sub-case (fixes finding 9 / H7).** The mandated "human does not
   349	respond" case is not uniform; coverage differs:
   350	
   351	| Sub-case | Covered by | Status |
   352	|---|---|---|
   353	| Distracted but present | escalation ladder summons attention | controlled if helm eventually responds |
   354	| Overboard | kill-cord (lanyard pulls) | controlled |
   355	| Displaced from station | kill-cord | controlled |
   356	| **Unconscious at the helm, cord still clipped** | nothing in present design | **UNCONTROLLED** |
   357	| Kill-cord not clipped | pre-trial checklist (procedural) | controlled only if checklist enforced |
   358	| Manual override mis-wired/failed | pre-trial test (procedural) | controlled only if tested |
   359	
   360	The unconscious-at-helm residual — propulsion continues at last physical state until fuel
   361	exhaustion or third-party intervention — is **not controlled by software and not accepted
   362	here**: this document has no risk-acceptance authority. It requires an **operational control**
   363	(a second qualified crew member, or a helm dead-man / vigilance device that cuts propulsion on
   364	loss of periodic helm input) whose specification and formal risk acceptance belong to the
   365	trial authority. Registered in §5; **the trial risk envelope should not permit unattended
   366	continued propulsion until this control is in place.**
   367	
   368	Pre-trial checklist (operational): kill-cord clipped; manual override tested; ArduPilot
   369	non-manoeuvre failsafe verified in SITL; Case-A revocation ordering verified in SITL/HIL.
   370	
   371	---
   372	
   373	## 4. Hazard table
   374	
   375	hazard → cause → mitigation → residual. Residuals marked **[UNVERIFIED]** are bounded only
   376	after GNSS-withheld replay and/or SITL/HIL evidence.
   377	
   378	| # | Hazard | Cause | Mitigation | Residual risk |
   379	|---|---|---|---|---|
   380	| **H1** | **Stale-solution steering** | Sparse absolute fixes; DR fill; covariance growth. | Covariance time-propagated from IMU every accepted sample (guards failure mode 5); G2 per-epoch PL; **`t_dr` DR-authority timeout** revokes on last-absolute-fix age even if covariance looks in-limit; G4 requires a live producer. | If the covariance model is itself optimistic (H2), a fresh-looking frame under-reports staleness; `t_dr` bounds this independently of covariance. Magnitude **[UNVERIFIED]** until withheld-replay validation. |
   381	| **H2** | **Optimistic covariance (wrong-Jacobian class)** — the gate consumes the very covariance that is wrong. | Wrong Jacobian (silent; filter still emits a covariance), missing propagation, mis-modelled process noise. | **Offline, pre-trial:** finite-difference Jacobian check; **NEES against truth in aided/withheld replay** (needs truth ⇒ offline only). **Online:** normalized-innovation-squared (**NIS**) consistency — flags innovations too large for the claimed innovation covariance, but is *covariance-coupled*, not covariance-independent; **cross-sensor redundancy residuals** (speed-log vs LEO ground speed, dual-magnetometer agreement, IMU-predicted vs measured) which *are* covariance-independent but limited in coverage; conservative process noise. | A slow bias that shrinks state **and** innovation covariance consistently evades NIS and lies below the redundancy floor; **not closed online**. Bounded only by conservative limits, offline gates and the human. **[UNVERIFIED]**. (Prior "NEES online, covariance-independent" claim withdrawn as technically wrong.) |
   382	| **H3** | **Authority flapping** | Metric noise near threshold. | Distinct `caution_enter`/`caution_clear` + `dwell_clear` (real hysteresis); latched revocation + explicit re-arm with `dwell_rearm`. | Mis-tuned band flaps or lags; values **[UNVERIFIED]**, frozen before trials. |
   383	| **H4** | **Silent estimator halt vs authority-alive inversion** | Estimator stalls/freezes while publisher stays alive. | `R` fires only on an *advancing* solution sequence that passes integrity; a frozen output does not advance the sequence ⇒ lease expires ⇒ **live** supervisor revokes (Case A). Watchdog on independent monotonic clock; its expiry cannot stop the estimator (baseline). | A bug re-emitting *stale-but-sequence-advancing* frames defeats sequence-freshness; needs a **content/innovation-liveness** check (registered §5). Whole-process death is Case B, not H4. **[UNVERIFIED]**. |
   384	| **H5** | **MAVLink link loss mid-authority** | Cable/USB/serial/connector fault. | This is **Case B**: internal revocation cannot reach ArduPilot. Actual responders: ArduPilot's pre-configured **non-manoeuvre** GPS-failsafe (SITL-validated) at its 4 s timeout, plus helm override/kill-cord (link-independent). Companion detects link loss via ArduPilot→companion heartbeat deadline → alarm/log only. | Unavoidable ≤ `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` (~4 s) coast on last `GPS_INPUT`; bounded, non-manoeuvring at timeout, helm dominant. Exact failsafe params **[UNVERIFIED]** until SITL-verified. The prior "`t_lease` guarantees the companion revokes first" claim is withdrawn (invalid across a dead link). |
   385	| **H6** | **`GPS_INPUT` spoof / companion producing plausible-wrong output** | (a) companion process-level fault; (b) external MAVLink injection. | (b) dedicated point-to-point companion↔autopilot link (not networked); companion sole authorised source (`GPS1_TYPE=14`); enable MAVLink signing (**[UNVERIFIED]** support). LEO-SoOP removes the *RF* GNSS-spoof surface; the MAVLink surface remains. (a) **No in-companion module is independent of a process-level fault (§3.0)** — the integrity monitor/watchdog can be falsified by the same fault; this is **not** cited as mitigation. | (a) **Uncontrolled by present design**: requires an out-of-companion-process independent monitor (does not exist). Physical kill-cord cannot detect plausible-wrong steering. **[UNVERIFIED]/uncontrolled — registered §5.** |
   386	| **H7** | **Human-override failure** | Distracted / unconscious-at-helm / overboard / cord unclipped / override failed. | Per-sub-case coverage table (§3.3): ladder + kill-cord cover distracted/overboard/displaced; checklist covers clip/override. Software never auto-manoeuvres, so an unresponsive human triggers no surprise manoeuvre. | **Unconscious-at-helm with cord clipped is UNCONTROLLED** by software; needs an operational control (second crew / helm dead-man) with formal risk acceptance by the trial authority. Not accepted here. **[UNVERIFIED]/uncontrolled — registered §5.** |
   387	| **H8** | **Frequency-reference/heel bias or total heading loss steering** | Reference degrades or sustained heel steps the drift model; both magnetometers lost. | Reject biased Doppler per integrity; G2 revokes on limit breach; heading PL revokes on dual-magnetometer loss; mount g-sensitivity vector vertical (baseline). | Slow in-model bias below the innovation-detection floor. **[UNVERIFIED]**; bounded by conservative limits and the human. |
   388	
